  <div class="container" style="padding-block: var(--space-12);">
    <div style="max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto;">

      <!-- REQUIRED disclaimer above the fold -->
      <Disclaimer variant="immigration" />

      <!-- Work From Bermuda closure — critical alert -->
      <div class="alert alert-closed" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);" role="alert">
        <strong>Programme closed — 28 February 2025:</strong> The Work From Bermuda digital-nomad
        programme closed permanently. It is no longer accepting applications.
        If you have read elsewhere that this programme is available, that information is out of date.
        Verify at <a href="https://www.gov.bm" rel="noopener" target="_blank" style="color: #991b1b;">gov.bm</a>.
      </div>

      <h2>How Bermuda work permits work</h2>
      <p>
        Bermuda requires a work permit for all non-Bermudians (and non-spouses of Bermudians with PRC status)
        to work on the island. There is no independent work visa — the permit is employer-sponsored.
      </p>
      <p>
        This means: <strong>you need a job offer from a Bermuda-based employer before you can legally move
        to work there.</strong> There is no path to move speculatively and job-hunt on arrival
        (unless you qualify for the EIRC investor certificate — see below).
      </p>

      <h3>The employer's obligations</h3>
      <p>
        Before hiring a non-Bermudian, the employer must:
      </p>
      <ol class="prose" style="padding-left: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">
        <li>Advertise the position to Bermudians and Permanent Resident Certificate (PRC) holders</li>
        <li>Demonstrate that no qualified Bermudian or PRC holder was available for the role</li>
        <li>Apply to the Department of Immigration for a work permit on behalf of the prospective employee</li>
        <li>Pay the permit fees (fees vary by salary band and permit duration)</li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        This Bermudianisation requirement is enforced. Employers in industries with available Bermudian
        talent face more scrutiny than those in specialist sectors (e.g. reinsurance, risk modelling,
        fund administration, tech).
      </p>

      <h3>Permit duration and renewal</h3>
      <p>
        Work permits are typically issued for 1–5 years depending on the role and employer.
        They are tied to the employer — if you change jobs, a new permit is required.
        Term limits (a maximum number of years working in Bermuda for foreign nationals)
        were removed in 2016, but this area has historically changed; verify current policy at gov.bm.
        <VerifyBadge date="2026-06-10" sourceLabel="gov.bm" sourceUrl="https://www.gov.bm/working-in-bermuda" />
      </p>

      <h3>Permit fees</h3>
      <p>
        Permit fees vary by the employee's annual salary and the permit duration. They are paid by the
        employer but may affect your compensation negotiation. Verify current fee schedules at
        <a href="https://www.gov.bm" rel="noopener" target="_blank">gov.bm</a> — fees are subject to Budget changes.
        <VerifyBadge date="2026-06-10" />
      </p>

      <!-- EIRC -->
      <h2>EIRC — Economic Investment Residential Certificate</h2>
      <p>
        The EIRC is Bermuda's investor pathway. It grants residential rights (not work rights directly)
        to investors who meet the minimum investment threshold.
      </p>
      <ul class="prose" style="padding-left: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">
        <li><strong>Minimum investment:</strong> $2.5 million in qualifying Bermuda assets or real property</li>
        <li><strong>What it grants:</strong> Residential rights — the ability to live in Bermuda</li>
        <li><strong>Work rights:</strong> Separate work permit still required to work for a Bermuda employer</li>
        <li><strong>Verify:</strong> EIRC rules have changed over the years — confirm current terms at <a href="https://www.gov.bm" rel="noopener" target="_blank">gov.bm</a></li>
      </ul>

      <!-- Spouse / PRC -->
      <h2>Spouse of a Bermudian or PRC holder</h2>
      <p>
        Spouses of Bermudians and holders of a Permanent Resident Certificate (PRC) have broader
        rights to work in Bermuda. If this applies to you, the pathway is materially different —
        consult a Bermuda immigration attorney for your specific situation.
      </p>

      <!-- Source / verify -->
      <div style="background-color: var(--color-ocean-muted); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-5) var(--space-6); margin-top: var(--space-10);">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); margin: 0; color: var(--color-ink);">
          <strong>Verify current requirements:</strong> This page is informational only.
          Work permit rules, fees, and term limits are subject to legislative change.
          The authoritative source is the Bermuda Department of Immigration:
          <a href="https://www.gov.bm/working-in-bermuda" rel="noopener" target="_blank">gov.bm/working-in-bermuda</a>.
          Consider engaging a Bermuda immigration attorney before making commitments.
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</Base>
